[src:automl/feature-selection] A recent method called regularized tree can be used for feature subset selection.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Regularized trees penalize using a variable similar to the variables selected at previous tree nodes for splitting the current node.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Regularized trees only need build one tree model (or one tree ensemble model) and thus are computationally efficient.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Regularized trees naturally handle numerical and categorical features, interactions and nonlinearities.
[src:automl/feature-selection] They are invariant to attribute scales (units) and insensitive to outliers, and thus, require little data preprocessing such as normalization.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Regularized random forest (RRF) is one type of regularized trees.
[src:automl/feature-selection] The guided RRF is an enhanced RRF which is guided by the importance scores from an ordinary random forest.
[src:automl/feature-selection] A metaheuristic is a general description of an algorithm dedicated to solve difficult (typically NP-hard problem) optimization problems for which there is no classical solving methods.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Generally, a metaheuristic is a stochastic algorithm tending to reach a global optimum.
[src:automl/feature-selection] There are many metaheuristics, from a simple local search to a complex global search algorithm.
[src:automl/feature-selection] The feature selection methods are typically presented in three classes based on how they combine the selection algorithm and the model building.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Filter type methods select variables regardless of the model.
[src:automl/feature-selection] They are based only on general features like the correlation with the variable to predict.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Filter methods suppress the least interesting variables.
[src:automl/feature-selection] The other variables will be part of a classification or a regression model used to classify or to predict data.
[src:automl/feature-selection] These methods are particularly effective in computation time and robust to overfitting.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Filter methods tend to select redundant variables when they do not consider the relationships between variables.
[src:automl/feature-selection] However, more elaborate features try to minimize this problem by removing variables highly correlated to each other, such as the Fast Correlation Based Filter (FCBF) algorithm.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Wrapper methods evaluate subsets of variables which allows, unlike filter approaches, to detect the possible interactions amongst variables.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Embedded methods have been recently proposed that try to combine the advantages of both previous methods.
[src:automl/feature-selection] A learning algorithm takes advantage of its own variable selection process and performs feature selection and classification simultaneously, such as the FRMT algorithm.
[src:automl/feature-selection] This is a survey of the application of feature selection metaheuristics lately used in the literature.
[src:automl/feature-selection] Some learning algorithms perform feature selection as part of their overall operation.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] In machine learning, **hyperparameter optimization** or tuning is the problem of choosing a set of optimal hyperparameters for a learning algorithm.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] A hyperparameter is a parameter whose value is used to control the learning process, which must be configured before the process starts.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperparameter optimization determines the set of hyperparameters that yields an optimal model which minimizes a predefined loss function on a given data set.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] The objective function takes a set of hyperparameters and returns the associated loss.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Cross-validation is often used to estimate this generalization performance, and therefore choose the set of values for hyperparameters that maximize it.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] The traditional method for hyperparameter optimization has been *grid search*, or a *parameter sweep*, which is simply an exhaustive searching through a manually specified subset of the hyperparameter space of a learning algorithm.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] A grid search algorithm must be guided by some performance metric, typically measured by cross-validation on the training set or evaluation on a hold-out validation set.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Since the parameter space of a machine learner may include real-valued or unbounded value spaces for certain parameters, manually set bounds and discretization may be necessary before applying grid search.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] For example, a typical soft-margin SVM classifier equipped with an RBF kernel has at least two hyperparameters that need to be tuned for good performance on unseen data: a regularization constant *C* and a kernel hyperparameter γ.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search then trains an SVM with each pair (*C*, γ) in the Cartesian product of these two sets and evaluates their performance on a held-out validation set (or by internal cross-validation on the training set, in which case multiple SVMs are trained per pair).
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Finally, the grid search algorithm outputs the settings that achieved the highest score in the validation procedure.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Grid search suffers from the curse of dimensionality, but is often embarrassingly parallel because the hyperparameter settings it evaluates are typically independent of each other.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search replaces the exhaustive enumeration of all combinations by selecting them randomly.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be simply applied to the discrete setting described above, but also generalizes to continuous and mixed spaces.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] A benefit over grid search is that random search can explore many more values than grid search could for continuous hyperparameters.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] It can outperform Grid search, especially when only a small number of hyperparameters affects the final performance of the machine learning algorithm.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] In this case, the optimization problem is said to have a low intrinsic dimensionality.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Random Search is also embarrassingly parallel, and additionally allows the inclusion of prior knowledge by specifying the distribution from which to sample.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Despite its simplicity, random search remains one of the important base-lines against which to compare the performance of new hyperparameter optimization methods.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Bayesian optimization is a global optimization method for noisy black-box functions.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Applied to hyperparameter optimization, Bayesian optimization builds a probabilistic model of the function mapping from hyperparameter values to the objective evaluated on a validation set.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] By iteratively evaluating a promising hyperparameter configuration based on the current model, and then updating it, Bayesian optimization aims to gather observations revealing as much information as possible about this function and, in particular, the location of the optimum.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] It tries to balance exploration (hyperparameters for which the outcome is most uncertain) and exploitation (hyperparameters expected close to the optimum).
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] In practice, Bayesian optimization has been shown to obtain better results in fewer evaluations compared to grid search and random search, due to the ability to reason about the quality of experiments before they are run.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] For specific learning algorithms, it is possible to compute the gradient with respect to hyperparameters and then optimize the hyperparameters using gradient descent.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] The first usage of these techniques was focused on neural networks.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Since then, these methods have been extended to other models such as support vector machines or logistic regression.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] A different approach in order to obtain a gradient with respect to hyperparameters consists in differentiating the steps of an iterative optimization algorithm using automatic differentiation.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] A more recent work along this direction uses the implicit function theorem to calculate hypergradients and proposes a stable approximation of the inverse Hessian.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] The method scales to millions of hyperparameters and requires constant memory.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] In a different approach, a hypernetwork is trained to approximate the best response function.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] One of the advantages of this method is that it can handle discrete hyperparameters as well.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Self-tuning networks offer a memory efficient version of this approach by choosing a compact representation for the hypernetwork.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Apart from hypernetwork approaches, gradient-based methods can be used to optimize discrete hyperparameters also by adopting a continuous relaxation of the parameters.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Such methods have been extensively used for the optimization of architecture hyperparameters in neural architecture search.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization is a methodology for the global optimization of noisy black-box functions.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] In hyperparameter optimization, evolutionary optimization uses evolutionary algorithms to search the space of hyperparameters for a given algorithm.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Repeat steps 2-4 until satisfactory algorithm performance is reached or is no longer improving.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Evolutionary optimization has been used in hyperparameter optimization for statistical machine learning algorithms, automated machine learning, typical neural network and deep neural network architecture search, as well as training of the weights in deep neural networks.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Population Based Training (PBT) learns both hyperparameter values and network weights.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Multiple learning processes operate independently, using different hyperparameters.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] As with evolutionary methods, poorly performing models are iteratively replaced with models that adopt modified hyperparameter values and weights based on the better performers.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] This replacement model warm starting is the primary differentiator between PBT and other evolutionary methods.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT thus allows the hyperparameters to evolve and eliminates the need for manual hypertuning.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] The process makes no assumptions regarding model architecture, loss functions or training procedures.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] PBT and its variants are adaptive methods: they update hyperparameters during the training of the models.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] On the contrary, non-adaptive methods have the sub-optimal strategy to assign a constant set of hyperparameters for the whole training.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] A class of early stopping-based hyperparameter optimization algorithms is purpose-built for large search spaces of continuous and discrete hyperparameters, particularly when the computational cost to evaluate the performance of a set of hyperparameters is high.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Irace implements the iterated racing algorithm, that focuses the search around the most promising configurations, using statistical tests to discard the ones that perform poorly.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Another early stopping hyperparameter optimization algorithm is successive halving (SHA), which begins as a random search but periodically prunes low-performing models, thereby focusing computational resources on more promising models.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Asynchronous successive halving (ASHA) further improves upon SHA's resource utilization profile by removing the need to synchronously evaluate and prune low-performing models.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Hyperband is a higher level early stopping-based algorithm that invokes SHA or ASHA multiple times with varying levels of pruning aggressiveness, in order to be more widely applicable and with fewer required inputs.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] RBF and spectral approaches have also been developed.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] When hyperparameter optimization is done, the set of hyperparameters are often fitted on a training set and selected based on the generalization performance, or score, of a validation set.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] However, this procedure is at risk of overfitting the hyperparameters to the validation set.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] Therefore, the generalization performance score of the validation set (which can be several sets in the case of a cross-validation procedure) cannot be used to simultaneously estimate the generalization performance of the final model.
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] In order to do so, the generalization performance has to be evaluated on a set independent (which has no intersection) of the set (or sets) used for the optimization of the hyperparameters, otherwise the performance might give a value which is too optimistic (too large).
[src:automl/hyperparameter-optimization] This can be done on a second test set, or through an outer cross-validation procedure called nested cross-validation, which allows an unbiased estimation of the generalization performance of the model, taking into account the bias due to the hyperparameter optimization.
[src:automl/model-selection] 75) state, "The majority of the problems in statistical inference can be considered to be problems related to statistical modeling".
[src:automl/model-selection] 197) has said, "How [the] translation from subject-matter problem to statistical model is done is often the most critical part of an analysis".
[src:automl/model-selection] Model selection may also refer to the problem of selecting a few representative models from a large set of computational models for the purpose of decision making or optimization under uncertainty.
[src:automl/model-selection] In machine learning, algorithmic approaches to model selection include feature selection, hyperparameter optimization, and statistical learning theory.
[src:automl/model-selection] In its most basic forms, model selection is one of the fundamental tasks of scientific inquiry.
[src:automl/model-selection] Determining the principle that explains a series of observations is often linked directly to a mathematical model predicting those observations.
[src:automl/model-selection] For example, when Galileo performed his inclined plane experiments, he demonstrated that the motion of the balls fitted the parabola predicted by his model .
[src:automl/model-selection] Of the countless number of possible mechanisms and processes that could have produced the data, how can one even begin to choose the best model?
[src:automl/model-selection] The mathematical approach commonly taken decides among a set of candidate models; this set must be chosen by the researcher.
[src:automl/model-selection] Often simple models such as polynomials are used, at least initially .
[src:automl/model-selection] Burnham & Anderson (2002) emphasize throughout their book the importance of choosing models based on sound scientific principles, such as understanding of the phenomenological processes or mechanisms (e.g., chemical reactions) underlying the data.
[src:automl/model-selection] Once the set of candidate models has been chosen, the statistical analysis allows us to select the best of these models.
[src:automl/model-selection] What is meant by *best* is controversial.
[src:automl/model-selection] A good model selection technique will balance goodness of fit with simplicity.
[src:automl/model-selection] More complex models will be better able to adapt their shape to fit the data (for example, a fifth-order polynomial can exactly fit six points), but the additional parameters may not represent anything useful.
[src:automl/model-selection] (Perhaps those six points are really just randomly distributed about a straight line.) Goodness of fit is generally determined using a likelihood ratio approach, or an approximation of this, leading to a chi-squared test.
[src:automl/model-selection] The complexity is generally measured by counting the number of parameters in the model.
[src:automl/model-selection] Model selection techniques can be considered as estimators of some physical quantity, such as the probability of the model producing the given data.
[src:automl/model-selection] The bias and variance are both important measures of the quality of this estimator; efficiency is also often considered.
[src:automl/model-selection] A standard example of model selection is that of curve fitting, where, given a set of points and other background knowledge (e.g. points are a result of i.i.d. samples), we must select a curve that describes the function that generated the points.
[src:automl/model-selection] There are two main objectives in inference and learning from data.
[src:automl/model-selection] One is for scientific discovery, also called statistical inference, understanding of the underlying data-generating mechanism and interpretation of the nature of the data.
[src:automl/model-selection] Another objective of learning from data is for predicting future or unseen observations, also called Statistical Prediction.
[src:automl/model-selection] In the second objective, the data scientist does not necessarily concern an accurate probabilistic description of the data.
[src:automl/model-selection] Of course, one may also be interested in both directions.
[src:automl/model-selection] In line with the two different objectives, model selection can also have two directions: model selection for inference and model selection for prediction.
[src:automl/model-selection] The first direction is to identify the best model for the data, which will preferably provide a reliable characterization of the sources of uncertainty for scientific interpretation.
[src:automl/model-selection] For this goal, it is significantly important that the selected model is not too sensitive to the sample size.
[src:automl/model-selection] Accordingly, an appropriate notion for evaluating model selection is the selection consistency, meaning that the most robust candidate will be consistently selected given sufficiently many data samples.
[src:automl/model-selection] The second direction is to choose a model as machinery to offer excellent predictive performance.
[src:automl/model-selection] For the latter, however, the selected model may simply be the lucky winner among a few close competitors, yet the predictive performance can still be the best possible.
[src:automl/model-selection] If so, the model selection is fine for the second goal (prediction), but the use of the selected model for insight and interpretation may be severely unreliable and misleading.
[src:automl/model-selection] Moreover, for very complex models selected this way, even predictions may be unreasonable for data only slightly different from those on which the selection was made.
[src:automl/model-selection] Below is a list of criteria for model selection.
[src:automl/model-selection] The most commonly used information criteria are (i) the Akaike information criterion and (ii) the Bayes factor and/or the Bayesian information criterion (which to some extent approximates the Bayes factor), see Stoica & Selen (2004) for a review.
[src:automl/model-selection] Among these criteria, cross-validation is typically the most accurate, and computationally the most expensive, for supervised learning problems.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] NAS is closely related to hyperparameter optimization and meta-learning and is a subfield of automated machine learning (AutoML).
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Reinforcement learning (RL) can underpin a NAS search strategy.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Barret Zoph and Quoc Viet Le applied NAS with RL targeting the CIFAR-10 dataset and achieved a network architecture that rivals the best manually-designed architecture for accuracy, with an error rate of 3.65, 0.09 percent better and 1.05x faster than a related hand-designed model.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] On the Penn Treebank dataset, that model composed a recurrent cell that outperforms LSTM, reaching a test set perplexity of 62.4, or 3.6 perplexity better than the prior leading system.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] On the PTB character language modeling task it achieved bits per character of 1.214.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Learning a model architecture directly on a large dataset can be a lengthy process.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] NASNet addressed this issue by transferring a building block designed for a small dataset to a larger dataset.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] For the reduction cell, the initial operation applied to the cell's inputs uses a stride of two (to reduce the height and width).
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The learned aspect of the design included elements such as which lower layer(s) each higher layer took as input, the transformations applied at that layer and to merge multiple outputs at each layer.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] In the studied example, the best convolutional layer (or "cell") was designed for the CIFAR-10 dataset and then applied to the ImageNet dataset by stacking copies of this cell, each with its own parameters.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The approach yielded accuracy of 82.7% top-1 and 96.2% top-5.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] This exceeded the best human-invented architectures at a cost of 9 billion fewer FLOPS—a reduction of 28%.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The system continued to exceed the manually-designed alternative at varying computation levels.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The image features learned from image classification can be transferred to other computer vision problems.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] E.g., for object detection, the learned cells integrated with the Faster-RCNN framework improved performance by 4.0% on the COCO dataset.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] In the so-called Efficient Neural Architecture Search (ENAS), a controller discovers architectures by learning to search for an optimal subgraph within a large graph.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The controller is trained with policy gradient to select a subgraph that maximizes the validation set's expected reward.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The model corresponding to the subgraph is trained to minimize a canonical cross entropy loss.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Multiple child models share parameters, ENAS requires fewer GPU-hours than other approaches and 1000-fold less than "standard" NAS.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] On CIFAR-10, the ENAS design achieved a test error of 2.89%, comparable to NASNet.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] On Penn Treebank, the ENAS design reached test perplexity of 55.8.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] An alternative approach to NAS is based on evolutionary algorithms, which has been employed by several groups.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] An Evolutionary Algorithm for Neural Architecture Search generally performs the following procedure.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] First a pool consisting of different candidate architectures along with their validation scores (fitness) is initialised.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] At each step the architectures in the candidate pool are mutated (e.g.: 3x3 convolution instead of a 5x5 convolution).
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Next the new architectures are trained from scratch for a few epochs and their validation scores are obtained.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] This is followed by replacing the lowest scoring architectures in the candidate pool with the better, newer architectures.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] This procedure is repeated multiple times and thus the candidate pool is refined over time.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Mutations in the context of evolving ANNs are operations such as adding or removing a layer, which include changing the type of a layer (e.g., from convolution to pooling), changing the hyperparameters of a layer, or changing the training hyperparameters.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] On CIFAR-10 and ImageNet, evolution and RL performed comparably, while both slightly outperformed random search.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Bayesian Optimization (BO), which has proven to be an efficient method for hyperparameter optimization, can also be applied to NAS.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] In this context, the objective function maps an architecture to its validation error after being trained for a number of epochs.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] At each iteration, BO uses a surrogate to model this objective function based on previously obtained architectures and their validation errors.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] One then chooses the next architecture to evaluate by maximizing an acquisition function, such as expected improvement, which provides a balance between exploration and exploitation.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Acquisition function maximization and objective function evaluation are often computationally expensive for NAS, and make the application of BO challenging in this context.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Recently, BANANAS has achieved promising results in this direction by introducing a high-performing instantiation of BO coupled to a neural predictor.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Another group used a hill climbing procedure that applies network morphisms, followed by short cosine-annealing optimization runs.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The approach yielded competitive results, requiring resources on the same order of magnitude as training a single network.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] E.g., on CIFAR-10, the method designed and trained a network with an error rate below 5% in 12 hours on a single GPU.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] While most approaches solely focus on finding architecture with maximal predictive performance, for most practical applications other objectives are relevant, such as memory consumption, model size or inference time (i.e., the time required to obtain a prediction).
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Because of that, researchers created a multi-objective search.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] LEMONADE is an evolutionary algorithm that adopted Lamarckism to efficiently optimize multiple objectives.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] In every generation, child networks are generated to improve the Pareto frontier with respect to the current population of ANNs.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Neural Architect is claimed to be a resource-aware multi-objective RL-based NAS with network embedding and performance prediction.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Network embedding encodes an existing network to a trainable embedding vector.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Based on the embedding, a controller network generates transformations of the target network.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] A multi-objective reward function considers network accuracy, computational resource and training time.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The reward is predicted by multiple performance simulation networks that are pre-trained or co-trained with the controller network.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The controller network is trained via policy gradient.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Following a modification, the resulting candidate network is evaluated by both an accuracy network and a training time network.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The results are combined by a reward engine that passes its output back to the controller network.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] RL or evolution-based NAS require thousands of GPU-days of searching/training to achieve state-of-the-art computer vision results as described in the NASNet, mNASNet and MobileNetV3 papers.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] To reduce computational cost, many recent NAS methods rely on the weight-sharing idea.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] In this approach, a single overparameterized supernetwork (also known as the one-shot model) is defined.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] A supernetwork is a very large Directed Acyclic Graph (DAG) whose subgraphs are different candidate neural networks.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Thus, in a supernetwork, the weights are shared among a large number of different sub-architectures that have edges in common, each of which is considered as a path within the supernet.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The essential idea is to train one supernetwork that spans many options for the final design rather than generating and training thousands of networks independently.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] In addition to the learned parameters, a set of architecture parameters are learnt to depict preference for one module over another.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Such methods reduce the required computational resources to only a few GPU days.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] More recent works further combine this weight-sharing paradigm, with a continuous relaxation of the search space, which enables the use of gradient-based optimization methods.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] These approaches are generally referred to as differentiable NAS and have proven very efficient in exploring the search space of neural architectures.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] One of the most popular algorithms amongst the gradient-based methods for NAS is DARTS.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] However, DARTS faces problems such as performance collapse due to an inevitable aggregation of skip connections and poor generalization which were tackled by many future algorithms.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Methods like aim at robustifying DARTS and making the validation accuracy landscape smoother by introducing a Hessian norm based regularisation and random smoothing/adversarial attack respectively.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] The cause of performance degradation is later analyzed from the architecture selection aspect.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Differentiable NAS has shown to produce competitive results using a fraction of the search-time required by RL-based search methods.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] For example, FBNet (which is short for Facebook Berkeley Network) demonstrated that supernetwork-based search produces networks that outperform the speed-accuracy tradeoff curve of mNASNet and MobileNetV2 on the ImageNet image-classification dataset.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] FBNet accomplishes this using over 400x *less* search time than was used for mNASNet.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Neural architecture search often requires large computational resources, due to its expensive training and evaluation phases.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] This further leads to a large carbon footprint required for the evaluation of these methods.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] To overcome this limitation, NAS benchmarks have been introduced, from which one can either query or predict the final performance of neural architectures in seconds.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] A NAS benchmark is defined as a dataset with a fixed train-test split, a search space, and a fixed training pipeline (hyperparameters).
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] There are primarily two types of NAS benchmarks: a surrogate NAS benchmark and a tabular NAS benchmark.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] A surrogate benchmark uses a surrogate model (e.g.: a neural network) to predict the performance of an architecture from the search space.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] On the other hand, a tabular benchmark queries the actual performance of an architecture trained up to convergence.
[src:automl/neural-architecture-search] Both of these benchmarks are queryable and can be used to efficiently simulate many NAS algorithms using only a CPU to query the benchmark instead of training an architecture from scratch.
